			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The issue I was just thinking about while reading the pregnancy thread is, how are these three morally different? 
<br />

<br />
I haven't really thought this question through 100%, but I think that throwing it out here will help. Why here? Because we have such a wide variety of points of view, people from all walks of life, that in any case the question will yield a nice variety of opinions. 
<br />

<br />
Returning to the issue at hand, in my opinion, people have a belief that abortion is morally wrong, while (from what i have seen), they also believe that the pill and condoms are OK. I guess that the argument is that abortion is wrong because you're in a sense taking a life, you've crossed that line; and for the sake of this argument, let's assume that this is the main reason people believe abortion is bad. The second assumption we're going to make is that people who use condoms use them all the time and according to instructions. In other words, if anything happens, it's a fault of the condom, not the people.
<br />

<br />
The first point I'd like to consider is why do people think that the pill is better than abortion? If you use the pill, and know how it works, the sperm can and do reach the egg, just that the egg doesn't have anyplace to plant itself and is thus ejected from the womb (a very rough description, but it'll serve). The day-after pill has the same effect (of destroying the lining of the womb), just compressed into one dose. In my mind, you're still stopping the egg from developing <span style="font-style: italic">after</span> it's been fertilized. If you draw the line that abortion is morally wrong because it's a life you're taking, you're in essence doing the same thing with the pill.
<br />

<br />
The second point is the difference between condoms and abortion. Condoms, if they serve their purpose, also stop nature from progressing and doing what it's supposed to. Now, the key words are if they serve their purpose. In reality, what it comes down to is that the condom broke/was ineffective/had a miniscule hole/whatever. 
<br />

<br />
Let's consider two couples; both use condoms all the time, and both use them properly and at the right times. For one of them, there is a problem with the condom (let's assume it's the least obvious, that the condom was defective and had a miniscule hole large enough for sperm to get through), and the couple gets pregnant. The other couple doesn't. Now faced with a child, the couple decides to get an abortion. What is the moral difference between the two couples? 
<br />

<br />
The couple that got pregnant experienced a fault in the condom, something they couldn't have known or done anything to prevent. And, when they decide that what they want is to correct that fault, people who believe that abortion is wrong put moral blame on them. How? In my mind, the couple didn't do anything morally different from the first one... What are your thoughts?
<br />

<br />
I realize that there are people who believe that sex before marriage is wrong, and any form of birth control is immoral, but let's look at reality: we live in a society where sex is influencing us, everywhere. From EQ (boobs/females in thongs, etc) to ads on TV to TV shows to peer groups. People want to be with others intimately, and let's assume we're talking about the part of the population that falls prey to these influences and has sex.<br />_________________<br /><span style="font-weight: bold"><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=709740" target="_blank" class="postlink">Wreak Havvoc </a> </span>
<br />
65th Master of the Orb</span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by Wreak Havvoc on Wed Aug 11, 2004 7:11 pm; edited 1 time in total</span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
