			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The first point I'd like to consider is why do people think that the pill is better than abortion? If you use the pill, and know how it works, the sperm can and do reach the egg, just that the egg doesn't have anyplace to plant itself and is thus ejected from the womb (a very rough description, but it'll serve). The day-after pill has the same effect (of destroying the lining of the womb), just compressed into one dose. In my mind, you're still stopping the egg from developing after it's been 'seeded' (sorry, lack of words here). If you draw the line that abortion is morally wrong because it's a life you're taking, you're in essence doing the same thing with the pill. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
not entirely true.
<br />

<br />
progesterone/estrogen combination pills work in three ways.  Estrogen works to prevent ovulation, basically tricking the woman's body into thinking it has already ovulated, then when the off week comes, the body releases the hormones, the egg is released, and immediately flushed out with the uterine lining and the period.
<br />

<br />
progesterone can help prevent ovulation, but it also thickens the mucous around the cervix helping prevent the sperm from getting past, thus if there IS an egg released, the sperm cannot get to it.  it also affects the lining of the uterus making it inhospitable to a fertilized egg, if one happens to be fertilized, and making it unable to implant.
<br />

<br />
so the average progesterone/estrogen combination pills work on those three levels.
<br />

<br />
there is the mini-pill which is progesterone only, which doesn't have the estrogen component.  though this pill is usually only prescribed to nursing mothers or women who are intolerant to the estrogen pill
<br />

<br />
basically, it comes down to when do you believe life to be viable?  catholics think "every sperm is sacred" (in the immortal words of Monty Python)
<br />

<br />
and some are pushing this belief on others:
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.prevention.com/cda/feature2002/0,,s1-7342,00.html" target="_blank">http://www.prevention.com/cda/feature2002/0,,s1-7342,00.html</a>
<br />

<br />
personally, i think as soon as an egg is fertilized AND IMPLANTED, it is a life...but sometimes death is a better option than what could be faced.  i am a very spiritual person and i truly believe the little spirits are released to be born again, but that is my personal belief.  I also believe in Karma and what goes around comes around, in this life or the next..or the next...
<br />

<br />
*side note*  while i can understand and even advocate abortion in some cases, i could never ever personally do it<br />_________________<br /><img src="http://www.geocities.com/najiwench/anni.jpg" border="0" />
