			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">My sources are all public.  Supreme court cases.  Bills introduced in Congress.
<br />

<br />
In 1973, Abortion became effectively legal across the U.S.
<br />

<br />
In 1976, pro-choice advocates expanded their power by getting a Supreme Court ruling rejecting the husband/father's right to have any say in whether or not the woman could choose to end his child's life in an abortion
<br />

<br />
In 1983 the courts told states they could no longer inform the mothers seeking abortions that the fetuses were human lives.  They could no longer require a waiting period before abortions.  They didn't have to tell the anti-mothers that the abortion they were about to receive was a major surgical procedure.  Basically, pro-choice advocates were able to push thru their agenda of not having to tell scared young women the truth about abortions, in order to keep up the numbers of women who would actually go thru with abortions.  I wonder if those same ppl who pushed for these changes would object if cigarette companies were allowed to suddenly stop printing their warnings on each pack of smokes, or if alcohol companies were allowed to stop printing their warnings on each bottle/can they produced.  Probably not, since it's the person's right to choose to smoke without knowing it can cause cancer...
<br />

<br />
Pro-life groups were able to take back a little bit of territory by pushing thru laws, and having them upheld, that allowed states to withhold money for the purpose of aborting pregnancies.
<br />

<br />
The original court cases allowed unrestricted abortions during the first trimester, and allowed partial restrictions on 2nd trimester abortions.  Because nothing is specifically said about 3rd trimester abortions, pro-choice ppl continue to push the line, seeing how far they can go with having kids killed before it becomes a crime.  Eventually a bill is introduced to make certain of these late term abortions illegal.  The bill was approved in Congress, but vetoed by Clinton.  Bush later approved the bill when it was sent back.  But there never would have been a need for such a bill had the line not been pushed forward to this point.
<br />

<br />
Those are my sources, albeit worded in a rather biased manner.
<br />

<br />
